programme.title: Wimbledon 2015
programme.desc: Highlights of the ladies' singles final from the Centre Court at the All England Club, where the Venus Rosewater Dish was awarded to the winner. Four of the last five finals have been completed in straight sets, and the crowd will have been hoping for a lengthy match on the penultimate day of the championships, as the successor to Petra Kvitova was decided. The Czech star was victorious last year against Eugenie Bouchard to add to the crown she won here in 2011 and, starting as the second seed this time, was one of the favourites to be involved this afternoon. Her clash with rising Canadian star Bouchard failed to live up to expectations of a close contest, with the court time of 55 minutes making it the fifth shortest in Wimbledon history. The last final to be decided in a third set was in 2012, when Serena Williams defeated Agnieszka Radwanska, and Williams just needed victory here to achieve the remarkable distinction of holding all four Grand Slam titles at the same time.(n)

programme.title: Wimbledon 2015
programme.desc: Live coverage of the men's singles final at the All England Club, where the successor to Novak Djokovic is set to be decided. The Serbian world number one claimed his second Wimbledon title last year following a thrilling five-set encounter against Roger Federer, denying the Swiss star a record eighth triumph. All five sets were close, including two tie-breaks, with Federer saving a match-point in the fourth, but his opponent eventually prevailed to become just the third man, after Rafael Nadal and Juan Martin del Potro, to defeat Federer in a Grand Slam final, and the second after Nadal to beat him in a Wimbledon final.(n)
